1
00:00:01,988 --> 00:00:11,518
The Hindrances We usually start our practice with high hopes and great determination, but after a while the rot sets in.

2
00:00:12,499 --> 00:00:20,047
We can't stop planning our next holiday, we get annoyed with ourselves for being so distracted and we try another few breaths.

3
00:00:20,987 --> 00:00:24,032
But we're so tense we can't feel anything in the body.

4
00:00:24,952 --> 00:00:29,818
We decide we're hopeless at meditation and should never have come on retreat.

5
00:00:30,219 --> 00:00:34,484
Misery sets in, we give up and soon we're dozing.

6
00:00:36,426 --> 00:00:44,454
All such difficulties in meditation are termed hindrances and are completely normal, part and parcel of spiritual life.

7
00:00:45,755 --> 00:00:48,057
Every hindrance is a form of suffering.

8
00:00:49,639 --> 00:00:50,039
Dhaka.

9
00:00:50,881 --> 00:00:54,444
Remember, Dhaka includes even minor irritations.

10
00:00:55,664 --> 00:00:56,345
Our job

11
00:00:56,697 --> 00:01:03,326
as we grope our way towards liberation is to understand Dhaka, fully understand it.

12
00:01:04,468 --> 00:01:07,313
Each hindrance is a golden opportunity.

13
00:01:09,156 --> 00:01:18,932
But there's a balance to be struck between welcoming the hindrance and relaxing so as to feel its Dhaka as a moment to moment experience.

14
00:01:19,914 --> 00:01:24,561
It's through sensations and feelings that we learn the Dhamma.

15
00:01:26,481 --> 00:01:39,876
We can overdo the welcome, rejoice at the first hint of suffering, delight in the chance to propel ourselves towards liberation, and we imagine ourselves as courageous warriors, certain of victory.

16
00:01:41,638 --> 00:01:45,861
But the felt experience of Dukkha is not at all delightful.

17
00:01:46,942 --> 00:01:49,066
It can feel like a deep wound.

18
00:01:50,527 --> 00:01:56,033
Only by embracing the wounds of humanity can we glimpse what lies beyond.

19
00:01:57,159 --> 00:02:05,631
For this, the warrior in us needs to admit their vulnerability, feel their wounds, and take care of themselves.

20
00:02:07,272 --> 00:02:11,337
It's quite a challenge to get the balance right, lifelong learning.

21
00:02:12,500 --> 00:02:15,743
An endless supply of patience is required.

22
00:02:17,605 --> 00:02:26,997
The Buddha described five hindrances, sense desire, aversion, dullness and lethargy,

23
00:02:27,704 --> 00:02:29,326
Restlessness and worry.

24
00:02:29,366 --> 00:02:30,949
Doubt.

25
00:02:32,872 --> 00:02:36,598
Don't worry if you can't work out which box your difficulty falls into.

26
00:02:37,038 --> 00:02:43,310
Just do your best to maintain mindfulness, knowing there's some hindrance afoot.

27
00:02:43,330 --> 00:02:48,277
After a while, the particular flavour of the difficulty may become more obvious.

28
00:02:49,793 --> 00:02:58,627
First, we have sensual desire, stimulated by lovely sights, sounds, tastes, sensations and aromas.

29
00:02:59,669 --> 00:03:04,177
In Buddhism, the mind is also considered as a sense door.

30
00:03:05,500 --> 00:03:08,705
There is a lot of pleasure to be had from mental activities.

31
00:03:09,286 --> 00:03:12,611
Why else do we enjoy reading, watching a film, planning?

32
00:03:13,334 --> 00:03:19,980
In fact, this is the main area of sensual desire that comes up during meditation.

33
00:03:21,622 --> 00:03:31,611
We're trying to follow the breath, but daydreams about food or sex or the great novel we're going to write are much more enticing than the sensation of breathing.

34
00:03:33,152 --> 00:03:40,020
The usual reaction for most of us is to get annoyed with ourselves, redouble our efforts to follow the breath.

35
00:03:40,961 --> 00:03:43,002
But a moment's inattention

36
00:03:43,320 --> 00:03:45,264
and we're off in fantasy land again.

37
00:03:45,283 --> 00:03:57,700
I always liked to write talks around personal experiences and was racking my brains trying to remember one until I recognised what was blocking all my memories.

38
00:03:58,782 --> 00:04:04,509
It was the sensual desire happening right now as I long for a good example.

39
00:04:06,633 --> 00:04:09,717
This illustrates the main problem with the hindrances.

40
00:04:10,337 --> 00:04:14,263
We're so driven by them, we don't notice what's driving us.

41
00:04:15,465 --> 00:04:18,269
Fish will be the last to discover water.

42
00:04:20,791 --> 00:04:25,978
When we notice we've got lost in fantasy several times, we need to take a step back.

43
00:04:27,040 --> 00:04:29,543
Ask ourselves, what's going on here?

44
00:04:30,725 --> 00:04:35,872
In my case, I'd acknowledge I'm trying to write a Dhamma talk.

45
00:04:36,291 --> 00:04:51,733
Very often that simple acknowledgement brings perspective and I can reflect that no Dhamma talk will bring lasting happiness, whereas meditation practice does bring me in that direction.

46
00:04:54,677 --> 00:04:57,021
Sometimes we just can't let go.

47
00:04:57,062 --> 00:05:03,531
We can't be bothered following the breath because we're so intent on indulging our fantasy.

48
00:05:04,321 --> 00:05:09,326
In this case, we let sensual desire become the focus for mindfulness.

49
00:05:10,987 --> 00:05:18,434
We can use the noting word desire, desire, as we feel the experience.

50
00:05:20,755 --> 00:05:34,327
As I explore this now, I feel pleasant sensations in my head, along with a very enticing imagery light that seems to contain the perfect example for the Dhamma talk.

51
00:05:35,269 --> 00:05:38,413
There's tension in the jaws and my chest.

52
00:05:39,634 --> 00:05:41,334
The breath for the moment is still.

53
00:05:41,394 --> 00:05:49,862
It's as if I don't want to breathe for fear of disturbing my wonderful example of sensual desire.

54
00:05:51,805 --> 00:05:57,189
As I continue to watch, the bright light gradually dims and fades.

55
00:05:58,350 --> 00:05:59,591
The tension relaxes.

56
00:06:00,973 --> 00:06:03,235
The breath flows normally again.

57
00:06:04,125 --> 00:06:07,250
desire has now burnt itself out.

58
00:06:10,254 --> 00:06:16,244
Because I've been mindful of the hindrance, I've now undermined the force of desire inside me.

59
00:06:17,365 --> 00:06:23,415
The next time desire arises, I find it easier to persuade myself to let it go.

60
00:06:24,576 --> 00:06:27,281
This is such a gift to our future selves.

61
00:06:28,663 --> 00:06:31,887
Trying to satisfy all our desires is exhausting.

62
00:06:32,762 --> 00:06:38,692
Each one gives a moment's pleasure, but then we're off again looking for something else.

63
00:06:40,714 --> 00:06:42,298
There is another source of pleasure.

64
00:06:43,319 --> 00:06:52,093
It's the contentment that comes from relaxing, realizing we have enough to satisfy our needs right now.

65
00:06:52,112 --> 00:07:00,846
This wisdom is strengthened every time we work our way mindfully through desire.

66
00:07:02,394 --> 00:07:12,685
So when we notice we're obsessing about something, the perfect birthday present, the perfect sponge cake, this is an indicator that sensual desire is at work.

67
00:07:13,625 --> 00:07:16,408
Congratulate yourself for having acknowledged the issue.

68
00:07:17,108 --> 00:07:19,050
Often that's the hardest step.

69
00:07:20,512 --> 00:07:24,036
Then C, can you encourage yourself to let go?

70
00:07:24,055 --> 00:07:31,423
Gently remind yourself how fleeting is the pleasure that comes of satisfying these desires.

71
00:07:33,276 --> 00:07:43,252
If, despite all your wise words, you're still hell-bent on imagining the perfect sponge cake, then let sensual desire be the focus for mindfulness.

72
00:07:44,293 --> 00:07:48,600
Feel its energy, any pleasant tingles, any tensions.

73
00:07:49,380 --> 00:07:53,007
You really want to experience the thirst for imaginary pleasure.

74
00:07:53,927 --> 00:07:57,072
It is a perfectly valid form of meditation.

75
00:07:59,415 --> 00:08:06,966
Suppose your mood has flipped and you're judging yourself harshly for being distracted by the silly desire for the perfect sponge cake.

76
00:08:08,007 --> 00:08:11,233
This is the second hindrance, aversion.

77
00:08:12,875 --> 00:08:16,480
Again, the hardest step is to notice what's going on.

78
00:08:17,562 --> 00:08:24,192
We're so busy condemning ourselves as bad meditators, we don't notice the fact that we're judging.

79
00:08:26,112 --> 00:08:29,336
But with practice, we get better at spotting this.

80
00:08:30,119 --> 00:08:34,666
And we say, oh, this is the experience of judging.

81
00:08:34,725 --> 00:08:38,052
And with that, judgment often stops.

82
00:08:38,832 --> 00:08:40,676
This is the magic of mindfulness.

83
00:08:41,616 --> 00:08:47,586
Anger, judgment and other stressful states often disappear on acknowledgement.

84
00:08:48,990 --> 00:08:52,895
We only cause ourselves suffering by mistake, unwittingly.

85
00:08:53,145 --> 00:08:56,690
As soon as we notice the suffering, we stop causing it.

86
00:08:59,393 --> 00:09:07,201
At other times, however, the anger or judgment runs so deep that noticing these isn't enough to bring them to a stop.

87
00:09:07,221 --> 00:09:20,537
In fact, they may get even stronger because now we're judging ourselves for being angry, angry at ourselves for judging, and we're going round in circles and we don't know how to get out of the loop.

88
00:09:21,006 --> 00:09:25,211
The hindrance of aversion can be a very painful experience.

89
00:09:27,773 --> 00:09:34,719
When we're assailed by aversion like this, we let the experience itself become the focus for meditation.

90
00:09:35,779 --> 00:09:41,203
We feel the tensions, the unpleasant sensations, how the breath is affected.

91
00:09:42,024 --> 00:09:44,067
We notice the stream of thoughts.

92
00:09:45,087 --> 00:09:50,052
And we're not trying to get rid of anger or judgment, but curious about it.

93
00:09:50,960 --> 00:09:55,767
We want to become intimate with the experience and learn to relax with it.

94
00:09:57,308 --> 00:10:01,695
This is a challenge as none of us likes to feel our anger, feel our judgment.

95
00:10:02,736 --> 00:10:16,917
But if we can persuade ourselves to just give it a try, the pain itself teaches us how to be more accepting of our human imperfections and more compassionate towards ourselves and others.

96
00:10:18,888 --> 00:10:22,394
Physical pain is one very common cause of aversion.

97
00:10:23,035 --> 00:10:28,264
It can stir fear, anxiety, anger or other forms of mental pain.

98
00:10:29,307 --> 00:10:38,344
Often we move automatically so as to relieve pain without first becoming mindful of the pain and the desire to move.

99
00:10:39,946 --> 00:10:40,827
Alternatively,

100
00:10:41,381 --> 00:10:54,114
The spiritual warrior comes crashing onto the scene, guns blazing, and we determined to sit rock still for the full meditation hour, suppressing any feelings of anxiety or vulnerability.

101
00:10:55,215 --> 00:11:01,081
If you sense this, or if the pain is too strong, then it's best to move.

102
00:11:02,481 --> 00:11:10,950
Move slowly and mindfully so that you can watch how the mind changes from aversion to relief

103
00:11:11,470 --> 00:11:13,032
As you get more comfortable.

104
00:11:14,354 --> 00:11:16,817
This is a valuable lesson.

105
00:11:16,857 --> 00:11:20,864
We realize that physical pain wasn't actually the issue.

106
00:11:21,745 --> 00:11:25,370
It was our mental reaction that caused the suffering.

107
00:11:27,452 --> 00:11:28,715
Pain is a great teacher.

108
00:11:29,495 --> 00:11:34,423
So we need to encourage ourselves to sit with it, feel it, learn from it.

109
00:11:35,179 --> 00:11:44,832
But we also need to take care of the body, respect our limits, and learn from those magic moments as we move to relieve the pain.

110
00:11:47,735 --> 00:11:51,221
The third hindrance is sloth and torpor.

111
00:11:51,660 --> 00:11:52,883
We keep nodding off.

112
00:11:54,225 --> 00:11:58,549
And again, the hardest first step is to recognize what's going on.

113
00:11:58,590 --> 00:12:02,975
We can get so overpowered by sleepiness

114
00:12:03,192 --> 00:12:12,302
so mentally dull that we can't even summon the energy to say, this is sleepiness, dullness, lethargy.

115
00:12:13,945 --> 00:12:20,513
Like all the hindrances, we want to experience this one, feel it, learn from it.

116
00:12:22,315 --> 00:12:25,919
So sit up straight, drag that head up into the air.

117
00:12:26,681 --> 00:12:29,864
Sometimes opening the eyes helps, letting in the light.

118
00:12:31,225 --> 00:12:32,827
Joseph Goldstein describes

119
00:12:33,043 --> 00:12:36,489
imagining his eyelids being held open by toothpicks.

120
00:12:38,032 --> 00:12:48,508
And though the waves of sleepiness came and went, they couldn't quite overpower him because his eyes were being held open by toothpicks.

121
00:12:48,528 --> 00:12:52,173
If that doesn't work and you're still nodding off, try standing.

122
00:12:53,395 --> 00:12:57,042
The Buddha also recommends mental stimulation.

123
00:12:57,543 --> 00:12:58,443
For example,

124
00:12:58,879 --> 00:13:01,001
You could repeat the Four Noble Truths.

125
00:13:01,743 --> 00:13:02,844
Think about what they mean.

126
00:13:02,884 --> 00:13:11,313
It's one time in meditation where thinking is encouraged, but only till you've woken up the mind.

127
00:13:12,094 --> 00:13:16,479
Then it's bye-bye intellect, hello sensations and feelings again.

128
00:13:16,519 --> 00:13:24,447
Once we've aroused ourselves enough to be mindful, our aim is to investigate the experience.

129
00:13:25,542 --> 00:13:29,125
Feel the dullness in the mind, sensations in the body.

130
00:13:30,268 --> 00:13:37,777
Usually there are pleasant feelings drawing us into a doze as well as unpleasant ones associated with our wish to stay awake.

131
00:13:38,417 --> 00:13:39,678
It's a rich mixture.

132
00:13:41,260 --> 00:13:50,672
I remember going through a lot of sleepiness on a retreat till I suddenly realised I was waiting for the sleepiness to pass so that I could then meditate.

133
00:13:51,412 --> 00:13:59,965
This was a big discovery for me as I could then recognize that same waiting mind state in many situations.

134
00:14:00,525 --> 00:14:10,500
When I was bored at a committee meeting, for example, each time I noticed the waiting state, I would then grow more alert, be able to participate.

135
00:14:11,201 --> 00:14:19,072
And this helped me overcome habits of laziness and passivity and to become more active and engaged in life.

136
00:14:22,023 --> 00:14:26,307
The next hindrance, restlessness, is sometimes felt in the body.

137
00:14:27,528 --> 00:14:32,533
We keep moving around, trying to get comfortable, or it can be felt in the mind.

138
00:14:33,214 --> 00:14:36,616
We flit off into one worry after another.

139
00:14:37,957 --> 00:14:49,009
Again, the major challenge is to take that little step back, recognise what's happening and say to ourselves, okay,

140
00:14:49,562 --> 00:14:51,865
This is the experience of restlessness.

141
00:14:52,827 --> 00:14:54,210
What can I learn from this?

142
00:14:56,932 --> 00:15:00,298
That simple acknowledgement is sometimes all that's needed.

143
00:15:01,318 --> 00:15:05,686
A moment ago, we were fidgeting and worrying, not knowing what the matter was.

144
00:15:06,206 --> 00:15:10,952
But now that we've recognised the problem, named it, our troubles are over.

145
00:15:11,833 --> 00:15:13,436
Such a relief when this happens.

146
00:15:14,057 --> 00:15:16,701
It really builds our faith in the practice.

147
00:15:18,250 --> 00:15:20,913
Sometimes it doesn't resolve so easily.

148
00:15:21,633 --> 00:15:26,177
We know we're restless, worrying, but we're still restless and worried.

149
00:15:27,558 --> 00:15:33,524
In this case, let restlessness itself become the focus for meditation.

150
00:15:34,927 --> 00:15:39,051
Feel the aversion, the desire to move, to think.

151
00:15:40,032 --> 00:15:42,934
You want to get to know the raw experience.

152
00:15:44,015 --> 00:15:46,958
Allow it to express itself.

153
00:15:46,979 --> 00:15:48,240
Watched mindfully,

154
00:15:48,743 --> 00:15:51,405
restlessness eventually burns out.

155
00:15:53,427 --> 00:15:55,710
But sometimes we can't manage to be mindful.

156
00:15:56,471 --> 00:16:01,417
Restlessness is too strong, keeps sweeping us away into worrying and fidgeting.

157
00:16:02,717 --> 00:16:16,572
In this case, it can be good to open the eyes, look at something calming like a plant or the sky, and this gives a broader perspective and the worries and fidgets won't so easily overwhelm us.

158
00:16:17,394 --> 00:16:18,615
We'll be aware of them.

159
00:16:20,519 --> 00:16:27,590
I was anxious, restless, worried for weeks after major surgery to remove my voice box.

160
00:16:28,491 --> 00:16:36,364
Luckily, my hospital bed was by a window and during the daytime, my eyes were glued to a big tree in the lawn outside.

161
00:16:37,385 --> 00:16:47,522
My body and mind were exploding with restless energy, but it seemed as though the tree could soak up all the impact.

162
00:16:48,413 --> 00:16:53,000
And during sleepless nights, the clouds in the sky did the same job.

163
00:16:54,864 --> 00:16:57,447
Sounds could also soak up my restless energy.

164
00:16:58,349 --> 00:17:00,732
I always preferred it when the world was busy.

165
00:17:02,355 --> 00:17:10,368
And although it was very unpleasant few weeks, it opened my eyes to the peace on offer from what I had often ignored.

166
00:17:11,410 --> 00:17:15,416
Trees, clouds, background sounds.

167
00:17:16,307 --> 00:17:22,037
I began to intuit a vast ocean of peace, cradling my restless mind.

168
00:17:22,978 --> 00:17:30,509
This was a beautiful discovery, a great compensation for the loss of my voice box.

169
00:17:30,529 --> 00:17:33,474
Learning to bear with restlessness is a wonderful gift.

170
00:17:34,276 --> 00:17:39,084
When it gets overwhelming, take whatever support you can from the outside world.

171
00:17:40,025 --> 00:17:44,491
A calming focus for the eyes, background sounds for the ears,

172
00:17:45,214 --> 00:17:47,999
the sense of touch can also be very soothing.

173
00:17:49,381 --> 00:17:53,726
I spent a lot of time fingering the bedsheets just to feel their texture.

174
00:17:54,708 --> 00:17:56,971
And sometimes walking can help.

175
00:17:57,731 --> 00:18:02,218
Not the very slow Mahasi pace, but a gentle meander.

176
00:18:02,959 --> 00:18:11,609
We're not trying to get rid of restlessness, but supporting ourselves as we feel its energies in moment to moment mindfulness.

177
00:18:13,582 --> 00:18:15,163
The final hindrance is doubt.

178
00:18:16,525 --> 00:18:20,990
We need to differentiate here between honest doubt and skeptical doubt.

179
00:18:22,151 --> 00:18:27,797
If you have never tried watching anger, you might doubt whether this could possibly be beneficial.

180
00:18:28,857 --> 00:18:30,378
This is honest doubt.

181
00:18:31,319 --> 00:18:33,261
We genuinely don't know the answer.

182
00:18:34,723 --> 00:18:42,811
Skeptical doubt is where we refuse to consider watching anger because we're not sure whether this could be beneficial.

183
00:18:43,518 --> 00:18:45,480
Skeptical doubt prevents learning.

184
00:18:46,342 --> 00:18:55,673
We're unwilling to take risks, unwilling to experiment, to find out for ourselves what is false and what is true.

185
00:18:58,076 --> 00:19:01,641
For many of us, doubt takes the form of self-doubt.

186
00:19:03,182 --> 00:19:09,711
We agree that the teachings are useful but are convinced we couldn't possibly do the practice.

187
00:19:10,061 --> 00:19:13,709
If this gets the upper hand, it becomes paralysing.

188
00:19:14,611 --> 00:19:20,142
We can't try out anything new, can't commit, can't take on responsibilities.

189
00:19:22,405 --> 00:19:26,755
Once again, the major step is to recognise what's happening.

190
00:19:27,730 --> 00:19:32,555
Instead of believing thought that says, I can't possibly meditate.

191
00:19:33,095 --> 00:19:35,396
I couldn't ever have any insight.

192
00:19:35,857 --> 00:19:37,398
I shouldn't have come on retreat.

193
00:19:37,838 --> 00:19:39,300
I might as well go home now.

194
00:19:39,340 --> 00:19:48,128
We pause for a moment, acknowledge this is the experience of skeptical doubt.

195
00:19:50,771 --> 00:19:52,292
This gives us some perspective.

196
00:19:53,013 --> 00:19:56,656
We can reason with ourselves, encourage ourselves,

197
00:19:57,109 --> 00:19:59,511
Is this part of a larger pattern in life?

198
00:20:00,353 --> 00:20:02,615
Doubting we can succeed at anything?

199
00:20:03,656 --> 00:20:11,384
Can we use the retreat situation as a golden opportunity to learn to work with this hindrance?

200
00:20:11,404 --> 00:20:26,019
We might still feel full of doubt, but so long as we stick with the retreat, do the practice, doubt has been undermined and self-confidence has been strengthened, that's not a bad exchange.

201
00:20:28,378 --> 00:20:33,344
Every hindrance cultivates the opposite virtue as we work through them mindfully.

202
00:20:34,444 --> 00:20:39,190
Working with sensual desire cultivates generosity and contentment.

203
00:20:40,371 --> 00:20:42,133
Anger transforms to goodwill.

204
00:20:43,513 --> 00:20:49,000
Mindful observance of sloth and torpor cultivates energy and resolve.

205
00:20:49,980 --> 00:20:58,368
And working with restlessness brings forth tranquility and doubt transforms to confidence and trust.

206
00:21:00,239 --> 00:21:07,527
This transformation comes about because we're learning to feel our feelings without believing their usual message.

207
00:21:08,548 --> 00:21:19,500
The feeling of doubt in my experience is most intense in my face, where the skin seems to shrink back towards my skull, prompting thoughts like, I can't do this.

208
00:21:20,740 --> 00:21:26,227
But I'm doing it anyhow, taking a footstep or taking another mindful breath.

209
00:21:27,448 --> 00:21:29,250
The feeling of sleepiness,

210
00:21:29,602 --> 00:21:36,191
is gorgeous and every bit of me wants to curl up around it and forget the outside world.

211
00:21:37,271 --> 00:21:43,881
But for mindfulness practice, I do whatever I can to stay awake and alert.

212
00:21:45,242 --> 00:21:46,625
Same with all the hindrances.

213
00:21:47,405 --> 00:21:54,494
We let them happen, feel the feelings, hear the thoughts without believing them.

214
00:21:56,095 --> 00:21:58,837
The hindrances are like emotional storms.

215
00:21:59,558 --> 00:22:09,249
It would be a relief to do the bidding of each storm, to go with the flow, sleep when we're sleepy, lash out when we're angry and satiate all our desires.

216
00:22:10,250 --> 00:22:19,480
But the relief is short-lived and all we've done is to sow the seeds of future storm and weaken our ability to deal with them.

217
00:22:21,041 --> 00:22:25,426
As they say, only dead fish go with the flow.

218
00:22:26,942 --> 00:22:30,631
If we go against the flow, be mindful of the challenge.

219
00:22:31,673 --> 00:22:38,125
This can be uncomfortable, confusing, but it's worthy work, ennobling.

220
00:22:39,189 --> 00:22:46,503
We are weakening the potential for future storms, cultivating emotional resilience and spiritual strength.

221
00:22:49,791 --> 00:22:58,876
May we welcome each hindrance as a golden opportunity to learn the Dhamma and walk the path to the end of suffering.

222
00:23:02,948 --> 00:23:04,813
The Factors of Enlightenment

223
00:23:06,008 --> 00:23:19,969
To help us bear with the hindrances, it's good to remember that just being mindful of these develops skillful qualities like patience and resilience, which in turn back up the strengths we need for Vipassana.

224
00:23:21,109 --> 00:23:23,733
These are termed the factors of enlightenment.

225
00:23:24,576 --> 00:23:33,028
Sounds lofty, but in fact these are very practical qualities that can be detected and developed in every meditation session.

226
00:23:34,492 --> 00:23:42,682
Panti Bodhidama uses the image of wild geese in flight, with mindfulness in the lead and the other qualities following.

227
00:23:43,963 --> 00:23:58,019
As you know, wild geese fly in a V-shaped formation, with one flank spread widely, almost abreast of the leader, pushing ahead, the other flank in the slipstream, taking it easy.

228
00:23:59,468 --> 00:24:12,363
This is a very helpful image because three of the enlightenment factors are stimulating, keeping us alert, while three have a calming effect, making sure we don't run away with ourselves.

229
00:24:15,226 --> 00:24:20,992
In the lead is mindfulness, sati in Pali, often translated as awareness.

230
00:24:22,375 --> 00:24:24,978
As we breathe in, we know we are breathing in.

231
00:24:25,018 --> 00:24:29,323
As we breathe out, we know we are breathing out.

232
00:24:29,944 --> 00:24:37,294
At one level, we're aware all day long, hearing sounds, seeing what's in front of our eyes and so on.

233
00:24:38,214 --> 00:24:40,778
But we're not usually aware of being aware.

234
00:24:42,058 --> 00:24:49,548
It's this level of awareness that we're cultivating in Vipassana, termed Sama Sati, right awareness.

235
00:24:50,650 --> 00:24:53,413
We hear a sound and we know we are hearing.

236
00:24:54,134 --> 00:24:55,075
Simple as that.

237
00:24:57,011 --> 00:25:03,083
And yet we very easily forget all about this simple and natural ability to know experience as it happens.

238
00:25:04,044 --> 00:25:08,952
We get too busy doing this and that to even notice that life is happening now.

239
00:25:09,934 --> 00:25:12,779
Not in the future with our great plans, but now.

240
00:25:12,819 --> 00:25:18,750
This sound, this footstep, this breath.

241
00:25:19,102 --> 00:25:22,226
These fleeting experiences can seem irrelevant.

242
00:25:23,287 --> 00:25:26,871
We assume we should be doing something, achieving something.

243
00:25:28,173 --> 00:25:32,057
It's very hard for us to believe that not doing is also worthwhile.

244
00:25:32,096 --> 00:25:47,234
It's only through mindfulness practice that we see how any doing, any judging, interfering, any attempt to achieve adds tension and stress to present experience.

245
00:25:49,325 --> 00:25:56,054
And thus, mindfulness trains us to relax, become content with being rather than doing.

246
00:25:57,715 --> 00:26:10,333
Within that magic combination of alert relaxation, we sense our minds opening, some vital energy stirring, some potential within us becoming conscious.

247
00:26:11,714 --> 00:26:13,257
This is satipanya.

248
00:26:13,574 --> 00:26:21,141
our intuitive intelligence, which is waking up and looking for the path to full awakening, enlightenment.

249
00:26:24,163 --> 00:26:30,049
To help us find and keep to the path, we have all the supporting factors for mindfulness.

250
00:26:31,391 --> 00:26:39,479
The first of the slipstream is called Samadhi in Pali, the ability of the mind to direct and rest attention.

251
00:26:40,519 --> 00:26:41,421
Unfortunately,

252
00:26:41,704 --> 00:26:48,757
Samadhi is usually translated as concentration, which suggests straining to hold attention.

253
00:26:50,420 --> 00:26:55,989
But think of how easily your attention is held by a good film, a story, a puzzle, a hobby.

254
00:26:56,789 --> 00:27:01,719
That's the flavour of concentration we are aiming for in support of mindfulness.

255
00:27:05,084 --> 00:27:07,407
The word focus is also helpful.

256
00:27:09,025 --> 00:27:13,211
We start by focusing on the sensations of the abdomen caused by breathing.

257
00:27:14,815 --> 00:27:23,351
If a sound grabs attention, we change focus and attend to the pitch and rhythm of the sound as we note hearing, hearing.

258
00:27:24,792 --> 00:27:33,648
If we find ourselves getting bored, restless, fed up, we broaden the focus to acknowledge that sense of restlessness or boredom.

259
00:27:34,912 --> 00:27:43,441
And to our surprise, perhaps, we might then notice the sensations at the abdomen coming into focus again, rising and falling.

260
00:27:45,604 --> 00:27:54,334
The concentration we develop in Vipassana keeps shifting its focus so that attention lands wherever it is naturally called.

261
00:27:57,656 --> 00:28:04,664
Concentration has a calming effect because it gathers our mental energies and trains them in one direction.

262
00:28:06,231 --> 00:28:08,174
Suppose we're lost in a foreign city.

263
00:28:09,457 --> 00:28:11,540
A thousand thoughts clamour for attention.

264
00:28:12,281 --> 00:28:13,483
Will I ask someone the way?

265
00:28:14,365 --> 00:28:15,586
Should I try that street?

266
00:28:16,588 --> 00:28:18,070
Should I find a police station?

267
00:28:19,413 --> 00:28:24,201
While the mind spins around like this, it grows more and more agitated.

268
00:28:25,222 --> 00:28:29,910
To calm ourselves, we choose to act on one and do that mindfully.

269
00:28:30,346 --> 00:28:32,288
It hardly matters which we choose.

270
00:28:32,910 --> 00:28:36,054
The important thing is to give the mind a focus for mindfulness.

271
00:28:37,155 --> 00:28:39,459
This will have an immediately calming effect.

272
00:28:41,742 --> 00:28:44,826
It's the same in meditation when any of the hindrances show up.

273
00:28:45,808 --> 00:28:52,617
The mind spins around trying to think our way out of the difficulty, but only grows more and more agitated.

274
00:28:54,480 --> 00:28:59,188
If instead we focus attention somewhere, the breath, the footsteps,

275
00:28:59,692 --> 00:29:10,669
the emotions underlying our disturbance, a degree of calm follows and we can bear with the disturbance more easily, learn a useful Dhamma lesson from the experience.

276
00:29:12,571 --> 00:29:23,127
The calming effect of concentration is balanced by the stimulating effect of energy, the leading factor in the wide flank of our wild geese formation.

277
00:29:25,471 --> 00:29:27,555
We have the physical energy of the posture,

278
00:29:28,648 --> 00:29:29,971
Experiment for yourself.

279
00:29:30,833 --> 00:29:39,107
Feel how much more alert you are when you sit up straight and how this dulls down as you let yourself slump.

280
00:29:39,127 --> 00:29:45,480
Standing is even more energising when we need an extra shot during bouts of sloth and torpor.

281
00:29:48,285 --> 00:29:51,130
There is also the energy that comes from resolution.

282
00:29:52,122 --> 00:29:53,482
Again, experiment.

283
00:29:54,565 --> 00:29:59,250
See how alert and determined you feel when you make a firm resolution to be mindful.

284
00:30:01,271 --> 00:30:16,327
Bhante Bodhidharma recommends St. Augustine's approach using the phrases I can, I ought, I want, I will to open four avenues for the energy of resolve to flow.

285
00:30:17,769 --> 00:30:20,593
Try saying I can be mindful.

286
00:30:21,484 --> 00:30:22,846
I ought to be mindful.

287
00:30:23,807 --> 00:30:25,049
I want to be mindful.

288
00:30:26,211 --> 00:30:27,232
I will be mindful.

289
00:30:28,634 --> 00:30:31,419
Repeat these to make their meaning sink deep.

290
00:30:33,122 --> 00:30:44,758
Although attention will still wander, you'll find it easier to rein it back in, gather it around the breath or footstep or whatever aspect of present experience is calling attention.

291
00:30:47,809 --> 00:30:53,420
Resolve itself can be strengthened by reminding ourselves of some broad aim for the practice.

292
00:30:54,761 --> 00:31:04,619
Although we let go of aims as we relax into present experience, we can remember them when we need to summon more energy to deepen our resolve.

293
00:31:05,545 --> 00:31:10,977
For example, bring to mind whatever inspired you to learn to practice in the first place.

294
00:31:12,098 --> 00:31:19,375
Maybe it was a book you read, a teaching you heard, a meeting with someone who radiated wisdom or compassion.

295
00:31:20,616 --> 00:31:25,106
Maybe it was an experience that gave you a glimpse of your spiritual potential.

296
00:31:27,314 --> 00:31:35,025
Having brought your inspiration, the goal for your practice to mind, you might find more meaning and depth in the resolutions.

297
00:31:35,486 --> 00:31:38,891
I can, I ought, I want, I will.

298
00:31:40,173 --> 00:31:42,375
Then let go, relax.

299
00:31:43,176 --> 00:31:50,587
Trust that those intentions will support your ongoing practice as you attend to the sensations of breathing.

300
00:31:53,925 --> 00:32:06,769
Thus our first pair of supports for mindfulness are concentration, calming us by gathering and directing attention, and energy, prodding us to wakefulness.

301
00:32:10,596 --> 00:32:14,262
The second of the slipstream factors is equanimity.

302
00:32:15,593 --> 00:32:24,281
This is an evenly balanced state of mind not disturbed by unpleasantness not enchanted and enslaved by pleasure.

303
00:32:26,944 --> 00:32:43,643
When something very enticing happens the sound of your name being called by a friend the taste of chocolate we usually react automatically looking around eagerly for our friend anticipating a pleasant chat devouring the chocolate.

304
00:32:44,837 --> 00:32:50,407
We're so caught up in our reaction, we hardly even register the initial moment of pleasure.

305
00:32:52,971 --> 00:32:59,943
If equanimity were established, we would feel the pleasure of the call, the taste, but not get excited.

306
00:33:00,945 --> 00:33:09,359
We would enjoy and appreciate the situation while knowing it as fleeting and unstable, not something to invest our hopes in.

307
00:33:10,353 --> 00:33:18,721
We might still look around gladly for our friend, but not be dismayed or disgruntled if they're already disappearing, waving goodbye.

308
00:33:21,965 --> 00:33:25,710
Equanimity develops as we encounter dukkha mindfully.

309
00:33:25,750 --> 00:33:32,438
Seeing how fleeting and unreliable pleasure is, we learn not to get so excited.

310
00:33:33,538 --> 00:33:38,605
Seeing that pain is impermanent, we grow confident that we can bear with dukkha.

311
00:33:39,631 --> 00:33:48,861
The mind grows less reactive, steadier, better at seeing the wider picture, more willing and able to bear the ups and downs of life.

312
00:33:50,422 --> 00:33:58,191
Equanimity is hard-earned, but worth every tear we shed, every gnashing of teeth needed for its cultivation.

313
00:34:00,712 --> 00:34:08,001
Equanimity is balanced by investigation of Dhamma, the second of the supporting factors on the wide flank.

314
00:34:09,297 --> 00:34:18,898
While equanimity persuades us to step back, see the larger picture, investigation requires us to cozy up to whatever calls attention.

315
00:34:20,521 --> 00:34:22,326
Say we're doing walking meditation.

316
00:34:23,708 --> 00:34:28,420
Investigation prompts the question, what is it I'm really experiencing?

317
00:34:29,614 --> 00:34:33,842
The question draws attention close to the basic sensory data.

318
00:34:34,943 --> 00:34:41,335
We feel how the foot peels off the floor, moves through the air, touches down again.

319
00:34:42,657 --> 00:34:45,262
Thinking can be temporarily suspended.

320
00:34:46,625 --> 00:34:54,237
But whenever it sneaks in to trap us in stories, plans, musings, we lose contact with the movements of the feet.

321
00:34:55,585 --> 00:35:09,780
Slowly it dawns on us that there's no room for my plans, my dreams, no room for anything I normally think of as I and me and mine, in that strangely familiar, fluid level of reality.

322
00:35:11,342 --> 00:35:13,724
There is only the awareness of the feet walking.

323
00:35:15,166 --> 00:35:21,271
A pleasant experience, but without room for the endlessly enchanting story of me.

324
00:35:24,525 --> 00:35:31,012
It's the mental factor of investigation that has led us to this strange and unsettling conclusion.

325
00:35:32,094 --> 00:35:43,588
We've brought our attention to the feet as they walk and discovered the Dharma, the truths that the Buddha claims will set us free from delusion, free from suffering.

326
00:35:47,271 --> 00:35:49,715
Investigation is based on curiosity.

327
00:35:50,434 --> 00:35:52,777
We want to know what's true.

328
00:35:53,246 --> 00:36:01,278
Without curiosity, meditation can help us relax, be happy, take it easy, stop trying to achieve anything.

329
00:36:02,519 --> 00:36:10,231
While this is indeed a welcome and healthy contrast to the busyness of modern life, it's not leading us to full awakening.

330
00:36:11,753 --> 00:36:18,342
It's only as we focus on detail that we start to see anicca, dukkha, anatta.

331
00:36:19,235 --> 00:36:29,711
How sensations and feelings keep changing whether we like it or not, and how unsatisfactory that is for our usual grasping sense of self.

332
00:36:31,054 --> 00:36:36,382
The up-close, microscopic view challenges our fuzzy view of the world.

333
00:36:39,637 --> 00:36:43,501
Any form of Dhamma study sharpens the factor investigation.

334
00:36:44,282 --> 00:37:02,708
Listening to Dhamma talks, taking part in discussions, reading scriptures and Dhamma books, all these stir curiosity, stimulate us to discover whether our own experience corresponds to that described in the talks, the books, the scriptures.

335
00:37:04,443 --> 00:37:21,141
If, the moment you start meditating, your mind settles into a blank daze and all your enthusiasm for Dharma study goes out the window, see if the noting word learning, learning, brings back that sense of curiosity.

336
00:37:22,862 --> 00:37:27,327
It helps if you can think back to happy learning situations in life.

337
00:37:28,304 --> 00:37:30,590
Did you enjoy learning how to ride a bike?

338
00:37:31,434 --> 00:37:32,177
Bake a cake?

339
00:37:33,300 --> 00:37:38,516
Learning is a challenge, yes, but how else are we going to grow any way wiser?

340
00:37:40,572 --> 00:37:53,751
For many of us, the notion of learning the truth about life, the universe and everything is so exciting that we immediately get lost in our speculations about what Nibbana is and isn't.

341
00:37:55,072 --> 00:38:10,494
Whenever this happens, we have to let go of heady excitement, bring ourselves back down to earth as gently as we can, so that this breath, this footstep can do their job of teaching us the Dhamma

342
00:38:14,137 --> 00:38:21,351
To help us calm down, we have the final factor on the slipstream of mindfulness, tranquility.

343
00:38:23,556 --> 00:38:27,143
This is the felt peace of a mind and heart at rest.

344
00:38:28,324 --> 00:38:35,418
It's a contentment with present experience, just the feeling of the foot lifting off the ground perhaps.

345
00:38:36,208 --> 00:38:40,295
It's hard to believe we can be content with so little, but we can.

346
00:38:41,416 --> 00:38:45,561
The advertising industry would collapse if we could all detect this potential.

347
00:38:48,306 --> 00:38:52,231
Whatever helps us feel relaxed and at ease cultivates tranquility.

348
00:38:54,072 --> 00:38:56,476
One way to do this is by auto-suggestion.

349
00:38:57,717 --> 00:39:04,748
We lay off investigation for a while and instead use the noting words, calming, calming.

350
00:39:07,208 --> 00:39:16,623
The idea of the breath as gentle wave can help as if we're in a hammock or a boat at harbour being rocked by rhythmic waves of breathing.

351
00:39:18,628 --> 00:39:24,458
Body scans can also be calming, especially if we focus on the limbs and bring attention downward.

352
00:39:25,619 --> 00:39:31,630
As you are breathing out, let attention flow down from left shoulder to left hands.

353
00:39:31,998 --> 00:39:39,706
Feel the hand resting on the lap until, at the next out-breath, run attention from right shoulder to right hands.

354
00:39:40,967 --> 00:39:47,072
Keep scanning down the limbs till you feel the mind settling, growing tranquil.

355
00:39:49,996 --> 00:39:57,903
One mistake that's easy to make is to expect tranquility to mean perfect, deep peace and disdain anything less.

356
00:39:58,880 --> 00:40:03,306
That's a bit like expecting to win Wimbledon when we first take up a tennis racket.

357
00:40:04,829 --> 00:40:13,842
We need to remember we're practicing, training, and that any move in the right direction needs to be noticed, encouraged.

358
00:40:15,103 --> 00:40:18,789
Look out for any pleasant, relaxing feelings in meditation.

359
00:40:19,530 --> 00:40:20,431
Appreciate them.

360
00:40:21,253 --> 00:40:22,255
Make much of them.

361
00:40:25,170 --> 00:40:39,630
Another danger, of course, is that we curl up around the pleasant feeling of tranquility and get dozy, or allow a lovely trance to take over, where we can fool ourselves that we're totally enlightened and don't need to do any more work.

362
00:40:41,434 --> 00:40:52,309
This is why tranquility needs the balance of joy, the final factor on the wide flank of our wild geese formation, pushing us onward.

363
00:40:56,152 --> 00:41:00,742
Joy in Vipassana can be understood as enthusiasm for practice.

364
00:41:02,065 --> 00:41:07,235
We want to continue being present, being aware, learning the Dhamma.

365
00:41:08,797 --> 00:41:14,148
Like tranquility, joy has a pleasant feeling, but it has more energy.

366
00:41:15,530 --> 00:41:18,617
It naturally follows from investigation of Dhamma.

367
00:41:20,369 --> 00:41:26,137
Investigation uses the mind's ability to solve a puzzle, sort out this from that.

368
00:41:27,599 --> 00:41:32,867
Joy is the feel-good that comes when we're engaged and interested in what we're doing.

369
00:41:35,431 --> 00:41:42,782
The joy of Vipassana is subtle and we might even believe meditation to be a flat, joyless affair.

370
00:41:44,398 --> 00:41:51,431
But it can be instructive to ask yourself, is there anything holding me to meditating a moment longer?

371
00:41:51,490 --> 00:42:02,389
If you can relax enough to find the answer, you will get a taste of the pasana joy, the joy of interest, curiosity.

372
00:42:03,612 --> 00:42:08,280
In this case, we're interested in finding out what's holding us to meditate.

373
00:42:09,239 --> 00:42:15,628
But any question asked mindfully will engage attention, cultivate the joy of a pasana.

374
00:42:18,333 --> 00:42:21,878
This joy of engaged interest is easily overlooked.

375
00:42:23,280 --> 00:42:32,496
Taking the time to notice and appreciate the experience is like cultivating a new pathway for the energy of life to flow again.

376
00:42:33,487 --> 00:42:40,920
The more we appreciate it, the more often our psychophysical energies will use this pathway in future.

377
00:42:44,326 --> 00:42:51,338
Another reason we fail to detect joy in meditation is because we tend to be overachievers.

378
00:42:52,679 --> 00:42:58,128
We want to be enlightened now rather than crawling slowly through the labyrinth of delusions.

379
00:43:00,016 --> 00:43:07,146
This is why tranquility makes such a good partner for joy in this final pair of our wild geese formation.

380
00:43:09,951 --> 00:43:17,141
Tranquility helps us relax enough to notice the joy of engaging with this puzzle we call the Dhamma.

381
00:43:20,306 --> 00:43:24,251
Another error is to cling to preconceived notions.

382
00:43:25,295 --> 00:43:34,202
We've heard of meditative joy as gorgeous tingly feelings all over the body, as if we're being massaged by an ocean of butterflies.

383
00:43:36,184 --> 00:43:41,989
And so we expect total over-the-moon rapture and disregard anything less.

384
00:43:43,471 --> 00:43:55,081
We have to be patient, realistic, remember that we're learning to enjoy meditation, and that again, each small move in that direction is to be welcomed.

385
00:43:58,706 --> 00:44:09,550
To recap, the factors of enlightenment can be imagined as a flock of wild geese soaring high in the sky in their classic V-shaped formation.

386
00:44:11,172 --> 00:44:13,398
In the lead is mindfulness.

387
00:44:14,179 --> 00:44:16,565
Breathing in, we know we are breathing in.

388
00:44:17,567 --> 00:44:18,588
Simple as that.

389
00:44:19,514 --> 00:44:32,355
on the wide flank prodding us onward our energy, investigation of Dhamma and the joy of being engaged in an activity so interesting and worthwhile.

390
00:44:32,375 --> 00:44:41,909
In the slipstream calming us down we have concentration, equanimity and lastly

391
00:44:42,396 --> 00:44:53,750
taking it very easy in this slow, slow slippage towards liberation, comes tranquility, the peace of a still, untroubled mind.

392
00:44:56,954 --> 00:45:04,202
In the Theravada scriptures, the Buddha says we must develop and pursue these seven factors.

393
00:45:06,342 --> 00:45:15,650
In a translation of a related Tibetan scripture by Analyo, the words are cultivate and make much of, which I like.

394
00:45:16,952 --> 00:45:24,340
We are to care for, appreciate, celebrate and make much of these seven factors.

395
00:45:25,922 --> 00:45:31,286
In turn, they lead to our long-lasting happiness and well-being.

396
00:45:34,742 --> 00:45:39,431
I remember seeing a documentary about a nomadic tribe in Nepal.

397
00:45:40,913 --> 00:45:53,635
Although their journey was challenging, hazardous, and for some proved fatal, the sentiment that inspired the trek was, it's the journey that counts, not the destination.

398
00:45:55,097 --> 00:46:00,126
This is the attitude we need so as to cultivate the factors of enlightenment.

399
00:46:02,688 --> 00:46:06,715
The process can also be likened to training a puppy dog.

400
00:46:07,695 --> 00:46:11,402
The trick is to reward good behavior, ignore the bad.

401
00:46:12,744 --> 00:46:14,327
So too in Vipassana.

402
00:46:15,268 --> 00:46:20,237
We don't make any big deal out of lapses in attention when the mind wanders.

403
00:46:21,179 --> 00:46:23,041
We just get straight back to the job.

404
00:46:24,288 --> 00:46:35,925
On the other hand, we look out for, appreciate, pat ourselves on the back for any traces of tranquility, joy or any other factors of enlightenment.

405
00:46:37,126 --> 00:46:39,128
It's okay to celebrate our successes.

406
00:46:39,929 --> 00:46:41,592
In fact, it's more than okay.

407
00:46:42,273 --> 00:46:43,275
It's necessary.

408
00:46:46,141 --> 00:46:55,105
May we soar through wide open skies to our true home, the peace and joy of liberation.

